            <div class="ins_notes">
                <span class="note" id="note-1"><a href="#ref-1">[1]</a> Not otherwise known.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-2"><a href="#ref-2">[2]</a> For public slaves cf. e.g. <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII31/431"><i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 1, 431</a>, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII31/445">445</a>, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII31/1154">1154</a>, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/RO/25">RO 25</a>, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IEleus/237"><i>I Eleusis</i> 237</a>; serving the Council, <i>Agora</i> XV 37, 4 (343/2 BC); <i>Agora</i> XV 62 col. 5, 10-18 (303/2 BC). This is the only epigraphical attestation of a formal supplication to the Council or the People by a public slave. Cf. <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IEleus/182"><i>I Eleusis</i> 182</a>, with notes. On public slaves at Athens in general see the concise survey of P. Ismard, <i>Annales HSS</i> 69, 2014, 723-51, helpfully summarised at <i>SEG</i> 64.2243.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-3"><a href="#ref-3">[3]</a> Athenian general during the Lamian War, 323-322 BC.</span>
